  .row.spacer
    .col-md-7  
      h2 What I did
      p I developed the content strategy for a team focused on redesigning Income Support, Jobseeker's Allowance and Tax Credits advice.
      p We distilled a sprawling and complex topic into a small number of logical user journeys. Then designed concise, user-focused content to meet user needs.
      p Practically, this meant we had to:
        ul
          li get to know our users and understand their problems
          li audit hundreds of pages of existing content
          li define existing and emerging user needs
          li design new content based on evidence and testing    

  .row.spacer.align-middle
    .col-md-7
      h2 Getting to know our users
      p We knew from research that, on the whole, Citizens Advice users have lower-than-average levels of digital literacy. And those who visit the site often do so during stressful and emotional times in their lives.
      p At the start of the project, we set out to observe as many in-person advice sessions as possible—both in and outside London.
      p I used this time to observe the way our users talked about their benefits problems, and to see how experienced advisers navigated these complex, nuanced journeys.
      p These experiences helped shape a content plan that reflected real-life user journeys, and a tone of voice that supported our users.
